                <head>327. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Secretary of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP_1">William Rogers</persName> met in
                    London with British Foreign Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DHSA_1">Sir Alec
                        Douglas-Home</persName> on July 11, 1970, and held talks with <persName
                        corresp="#p_DHSA_1">Douglas-Home</persName> and British Prime Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_HE_1">Edward Heath</persName> the following day. The
                    discussions covered a wide range of issues including British participation in
                    the European Community, <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> and European
                    security issues, African policy, relations with <persName corresp="#p_FF_1"
                        >Franco</persName>’s Spain, and trade questions. <persName
                        corresp="#p_RWP_1">Rogers</persName>’s reports on these meetings are in the
                    National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                        >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 727, Country Files—Europe, United Kingdom, Vol. III.
                </p>
            </div>
